Make an object density map¶

By using GROUP BY, we can aggregate in specified bins. In this next query, the GROUP BY clause tells the database to aggregate the results by the values in the nest4096 column, and return the average RA and Dec of objects in those groups, as well as the nest4096 value itself and the count of the number of objects in the group.

The long selection block using wavg_spread_model_i is defined in the DES DR1 release paper as the set of criteria so select point-like sources.

In [3]:
# select point sources with g-r<0.75, g>19.5, and gerr<0.2
desquery = """
SELECT avg(ra) as ra0,
       avg(dec) as dec0,
       nest4096,
       count(nest4096) as nb
FROM des_dr1.main
WHERE wavg_spread_model_i>(-90)
AND mag_auto_g<90
AND (mag_auto_g-mag_auto_r)<0.75
AND mag_auto_g>19.5
AND magerr_auto_g<0.2
AND (((wavg_spread_model_i + 3*wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.005 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i + wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.003 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i - wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.003
     ) OR (
      (wavg_spread_model_i + 3*wavg_spreaderr_model_i)>=0.005 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i + wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.003 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i - wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.003
     ) OR (
      (wavg_spread_model_i + 3*wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.005 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i + wavg_spreaderr_model_i)>=0.003 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i - wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.003
     ) OR (
      (wavg_spread_model_i + 3*wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.005 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i + wavg_spreaderr_model_i)<0.003 AND
      (wavg_spread_model_i - wavg_spreaderr_model_i)>=0.003
     )
    )
GROUP BY nest4096
"""
In [4]:

Making the Healpix map¶

A Healpix map is simply a one-dimensional array with number of elements set by the NSIDE parameter, which is the number of times the base Healpixels are split. We can visualize it as a map using the healpy library.

In [7]:
tmap = np.zeros(hp.nside2npix(4096))

Function for plotting on the sphere¶

In [8]:
def plot_sphere(m,fig=None,rot=(20,-30,0),cmap='viridis',half_sky=True,notext=True,log=True,coord='C',min_=None,max_=None,mark=None):
    m_ = copy(m)
    m_[m_<=0] = hp.UNSEEN
    if log is True:
        MIN = m_[m_>0].min()
#        m_[m_<=0] = 1*MIN
        m_ = np.log10(m_)
    if fig is None:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    hp.orthview(m_,nest=True,min=min_,max=max_,fig=1,rot=rot,cmap=cmap,coord=coord,half_sky=half_sky,norm='linear',notext=notext)
    hp.graticule(c='w')
    
    if mark is not None:
        ra, dec = mark
        phi = ra
        theta = dec
        foo=hp.projplot(phi,theta,marker='o',ms=30,mec='w',mfc='none',mew=3,coord='C',lonlat=True,markersize=10,direct=False)
    
    return fig

Populating the Healpix map¶

Now we set the elements of our Healpix map to the number of objects returned by the query, calculate the center of the RA and Dec distribution of the objects, and use healpy's orthview to visualize the output. We'll use a logarithmic version of the map for the visualization. We'll also overplot the location of the Galactic plane. Healpy allows you to mix equatorial (coord='C') and Galactic (coord='G') coordinates.

In [9]:
tmap[df_desdensity['nest4096']] = df_desdensity['nb']
In [10]:
fig = plot_sphere(tmap,cmap='winter')

An NSIDE 4096 healpix map is pretty high resolution (~1 arcmin). If we downgrade the resolution to NSIDE = 256, it helps bring out low surface brightness features.

In [11]:
map256 = hp.ud_grade(tmap,256,order_in='NESTED',order_out='NESTED')
In [12]:
fig = plot_sphere(map256,cmap='winter',max_=None)

Plot again with an upper cutoff to bring out the inhomogeneity better¶

fig = plot_sphere(map256,cmap='winter',max_=0.3)

Query for photometry to make a CMD¶

In [20]:
# spatial query around the position, with cuts on mags, magerr (SNR) 
query = """
SELECT mag_auto_g as g, mag_auto_r as r
FROM des_dr1.main
WHERE q3c_radial_query(ra,dec,%f,%f,%f)
AND mag_auto_g between 9 and 25
AND mag_auto_r between 9 and 25
AND magerr_auto_g < 0.2
AND magerr_auto_r < 0.2
""" % (ra,dec,0.3)

print(query)

Plot a CMD¶

In [22]:
def plot_cmd(x,y,title='',xlim=(-1,2),ylim=(25.5,16)):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax.scatter(x,y,marker='.',s=0.3, alpha=0.5)
    ax.set_xlabel('g - r')
    ax.set_ylabel('g')
    ax.set_xlim(xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(ylim)
    ax.set_title(title)
In [23]:
plot_cmd(df['g']-df['r'],df['g'],title='Fornax DG CMD')
